               <floruit>3rdC<ref corresp="#d2e10051"/>
               </floruit>
               <note xml:id="d2e9995" n="12"> So in the London – BL Harl.
                            5508 (400) Ms. This person was obviously not well known, and his name
                            was not stable so that the scribes of the mss were not sure how to write
                            it, see vol. 4, Introduction 5.2.1.1.2.1.1, pp. 23-4. For this form see
                            under Gurya S-H/M.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e9999" n="13"> So in the Vilna and Pesaro prints and in
                            the Goettingen 3 Ms, see previous note. For this form see above, n.
                            8.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e10003" n="14"> So in the Vatican 487 and in the Oxford Opp. Add.
                            fol. 23 Mss, see above, n. 13. For the name זיגור see vol. 4, under
                            Zighru (1) I/M, p. 206.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e10007" n="15"> So in the Cambridge T-S F2
                            (2) 73 Ms, see above, n. 13. For the name זיגור see previous
                        note.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e10011" n="16"> So in the Munich 140 Ms, see above, n. 13 and n.
                            8. </note>
               <note xml:id="d2e10016" n="17"> So in the Vatican 134 Ms, see above n. 13. The
                            fall of the ב is probably a scribal error, see vol. 3, Introduction
                            2.8.2, p. 20.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e10020" n="18"> So in the Munich 95 Ms, see above, n 13. For
                            this form see vol. 4, under Ze‘ira (3) S-H/M, p.
                    356.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e10034" n="19"> Although his
                            son is mentioned only here in BT, he reacts to the words of Palestinian
                            sages (see Introduction 5.3.2.3) and in Hebrew, see Introduction
                            5.1.3.2.5.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e10051" n="20"> His son was a contemporary of the last tannaim,
                            see Introduction 7.4.1.</note>
            </person>
